---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import NewsletterSignup from '../components/NewsletterSignup.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Why we started A Green Family — and what we believe about sustainable living for real families."
>
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-14">

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="mb-10 text-center">
      <p class="text-6xl mb-4">🌿</p>
      <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl text-forest mb-3">About A Green Family</h1>
      <p class="text-ink-muted text-lg leading-relaxed">
        We're not the greenest family. We're just trying to do better — and sharing what actually works.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Story section -->
    <div class="prose prose-green prose-lg max-w-none">

      <h2>Where we come from</h2>
      <p>
        My wife and I both grew up in the countryside in Latin America — in communities shaped by European immigrants who brought their old-world habits with them and never let go. Cooking happened on wood stoves. The garden produced much of what the family ate. There were animals in the yard. Food scraps went to the chickens or the compost heap, which fed the garden, which fed the family. The loop closed naturally, without anyone calling it sustainable.
      </p>
      <p>
        Shopping was sparse. You bought what you couldn't grow or make yourself, and not much else. Nothing left the household without being completely used. This wasn't environmentalism — it was just how things worked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then we moved, built careers, had kids, and somehow slipped into the habits of buying more, discarding more, and not thinking too hard about where things came from or where they went. It happened gradually, the way most things do.
      </p>

      <h2>Why we started paying attention again</h2>
      <p>
        We're a family of four — two kids, a dog, a house in the Seattle suburbs, two cars (one electric, one not yet). A normal family, by most measures. But a few years ago we started actually looking at what we were consuming and what we were throwing away, and we didn't love what we saw.
      </p>
      <p>
        The funny thing is that the solutions we landed on weren't new to us. Composting, cloth over disposable, buying secondhand, cooking from scratch, reusing containers — these are all things we grew up with. We weren't discovering sustainability. We were remembering it.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's what this site is about. Not a revolution. A return.
      </p>

      <h2>What you'll find here</h2>
      <p>
        Every article is grounded in what we've actually tried in our own home — with real kids, a real kitchen, and a real budget. We're not perfect at any of this. We still have a roll of paper towels in the cabinet. We still buy things in plastic sometimes. But we've made changes that stuck, and those are the ones worth writing about.
      </p>
      <p>
        We focus on things that are practical for families — swaps that save money as well as reducing waste, habits that can survive busy school weeks, ideas you can involve kids in without making it a lecture. When a product genuinely helps, we'll mention it. Some of those links are affiliate links — if you buy through them we earn a small commission, at no extra cost to you. You can read the full <a href="/disclosure">affiliate disclosure here</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Our philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        Progress over perfection. A family that composts their food scraps and stopped buying paper towels is doing more than one that's planning the perfect zero-waste overhaul for someday. Small habits, done consistently, add up. We've seen it in our own home.
      </p>
      <p>
        We write from one family to another — not as experts, not as activists, but as people who've found that returning to simpler habits is usually cheaper, usually easier, and usually better in almost every direction. That's the whole idea.
      </p>

      <h2>Get in touch</h2>
      <p>
        Have a tip that works in your house? A topic you'd like us to cover? Email us at <a href="mailto:hello@agreenfamily.com">hello@agreenfamily.com</a> — we read everything.
      </p>

    </div>

    <!-- Newsletter -->
    <NewsletterSignup />

  </article>
</Layout>
